snippet.textDisplay:
So, a weird bit of advice for people with problems with getting gelatins and stuff to unmold - a centrifugal force is more efficient to get something unstuck from a surface. As silly as it sounds, if you hold the mold upside down with whatever surface you're unmolding onto underneath (as Emily does in this video) instead of shaking, jump while spinning around in a circle. It works pretty much every time.
As far as the jelly layer not packing a punch - I think using jam might be better. My reasoning being that because jelly is essentially just juice + pectin to give it a firm texture where jams use less added pectin. Pectin is going to be in any fruit product as it is because fruits naturally contain pectin. However, less added pectin, plus the looser texture of a jam would probably make it easier to dissolve, so you could probably go heavier on the jam to give it a denser fruit flavor. Also, you'd have less added sweetener than a juice would likely have. Food science stuff.
